               {:contains_hatespeech => false, :title => "The next president", :date => DateTime.parse('December 3, 2012'), :link => "http://www.dailytrust.com.ng/index.php/other-sections/opinion/182476-the-next-president", :text => %{We talk too much: Jonathan should not contest in 2015; it is the turn of an Igbo president; only a progressive should succeed Jonathan; The North must produce the next president…. Not many people seem to be interested in the ideological coloring of the next president. It seems everyone is resigned to the fact that the People’s Democratic Party, PDP, will always produce the president; therefore they reason that if there is any fight to be staged for the presidency of Nigeria it has to be within the confines of the PDP. I beg to differ. PDP derives a good measure of its strength from the disarray in the other major parties. If the ACN, ANPP, APGA and CPC can be cured of their provincial fixations and if the gargantuan egos of their ‘principalities and powers’ can be reined in for the purpose of achieving broad-based consensus, I wager that the new coalition will give PDP a run for its money in 2015. If wishes were horses beggars would ride, said Shakespeare. I know that one of the most difficult things on Planet Earth is to get Nigerian politicians to agree on anything unless the discussion is about personal entitlements from the common till. The mindset of the average politician can be summarized thus: “it is better to be a king in hell than to be a servant in heaven”. So, even if a ‘progressive’ politician is with strange bedfellows in a ‘winning’ party, he would rather stay there than foray afield for a party that espouses his egalitarian beliefs. In the same way, a conservative politician would prefer to remain in a ‘winning’ progressive party; a bird in hand is more than a thousand in the forest. You don’t have to like President Jonathan to concede to him the fact that he has largely allowed democratic traditions to thrive in the way he has refrained from tampering with the process in both the Edo and Ondo gubernatorial elections. Now PDP has to take the trouble of winning elections in a state or local government instead of merely capturing the constituency as happened in the past. I see a situation where, if Jonathan loses the next election, he will head to his village instead of going to the tribunal. I cannot say the same for his party; PDP without power will be like fish out of water. Now is the best time for the other major parties to merge and fashion out a manifesto that takes cognisance of the current challenges confronting Nigeria. Our people no longer want a government of ‘anything goes’. Their imagination can be challenged with a people-oriented programme of deliverables. I have heard pessimists say that the day when opposition politicians will come together for the good of Nigeria will not arrive. Nothing in my life experience convinces me that dysfunctionality is an essential component of the psychological makeup of the opposition in Nigeria. I agree that it will not be easy shoving aside the oversized egos of some of the notable politicians in the various parties, but that doesn’t mean that it cannot be done. It is expected that a spirit of give-and-take will permeate the merger process to avoid the usual Nigerian predilection for terms like ‘founders’ and ‘joiners’. Many a Nigerian would rather be a believer in the boundless creative possibilities available to turn our political landscape around than join the doleful queue of political jobbers chanting fi-di-fi forever. The other side of this political engineering is that PDP itself will not sit idly and watch the opposition push it off the throne. The ruling party has the means to literally buy division in several of the opposition parties. PDP can sow discord in the other parties in much the same way as it has reportedly done these past years. But will it succeed this time around, especially as the other parties are now aware of the trick? As stated above, our politicians obviously believe that PDP will still form the next government. This belief runs across the political divide. Otherwise there won’t be so much bad blood among the various ethnic champions who cannot conceive of a better life for their people unless a fellow villager or tribesman is enthroned as president. So we have been seeing politicians from opposition parties who campaign that Jonathan should not run in 2015. One lawyer even went to court to try and secure an injunction to prevent the president from running. I have always thought that all that is diversionary. Let Jonathan run if he wants. What will not be excusable is if the opposition parties don’t seize this opportunity to come together and present Nigerians with a viable alternative. If they fail to do the needful and just continue hoping that God will come down from His heavenly Throne to bail out Nigeria from our self-inflicted stagnation, they will wait forever and, dare I add, PDP will rule Nigeria, not just for the next 60 years predicted by Audu Ogbe when the going was good, but forever and ever. I know you won’t say Amen in a hurry. Dead president? A patriot recently sent me the following piece culled from the Facebook page of the Rev. Uma Ukpai: “Only a dead man can rule this country, a man who does not care whether he lives or dies, a man who has forgotten the pleasures of life, a man who is no longer interested in acquiring anything others die for, a man who has become blind to his own needs, who prefers to die than live, a man who says whatever it takes, whenever it is necessary. I want to see Nigeria move as a united nation. But a man that is living, that feels pains, that values life and celebrates life and enjoys the pleasures of life cannot be a national leader of this country”.}},
               {:contains_hatespeech => false, :title => "Must govt increase fees to provide good education?", :date => DateTime.parse('December 3, 2012'), :link => "http://www.dailytrust.com.ng/index.php/other-sections/letters/182479-must-govt-increase-fees-to-provide-good-education", :text => %{Education, according to ancient and modern thinkers is a social enterprise. Education is a “public good or service” which cannot be undertaken successfully by an individual. Other categories of such “goods or services” are public infrastructures such as roads, electricity and health. Hence it behoves on those responsible for superintending over the affairs of a society in this case government to provide free and qualitative education otherwise called basic or rudimentary education for the first nine years of education. The imperative of doing this should not be underestimated because as the name implies it is at this stage that the rudiments of basic or primary numerate, literate and logical reasoning skills are imparted into the psyche of the young ones in the society. It is also expected that once the young ones are able to pass through this stage successfully they become equipped with lifelong skills with the concomitant effect on general societal growth. At this level [1st nine years of education] education is presumed to be free and should also be qualitative for all members of the society. This is what can be referred to as the government’s fulfilment of its own part of the social contract to its citizens. The social contract is the organizing principle for most modern states/societies and it is guided by what is known as the norm of reciprocity which simply means for leaders to expect obedience and compliance from their followers they must fulfil certain fundamental principles one of which is the guarantee of the right to and access to qualitative education for all citizens, hence at this stage any leader that cannot guarantee this in these modern times presides over a decaying society and cannot command the respect of his/her followers and it will only be a matter of time before the society implodes. Hence the question of paying tuition within the first nine years of education should not even arise talk less of increasing it. However, at the later stages of education [post nine years of education] we begin to fall back on our conceptual framework where we were able to establish that education is an enormous enterprise where one party or an individual alone cannot adequately fund qualitative education. The question of subsidizing education begins to arise. In this case government still carries the task of subsidizing education by at least fifty per cent till the tertiary levels. This the government can do by partnering with the various stakeholders of education in the society. In conclusion, the nature of education as a “public good/service” does not really give room for any mercantilist approach as a sine qua non for quality education, contrary to this is the situation in most private schools in Nigeria at present where there is no positive correlation between the amount paid as tuition and quality of education but rather quality education is best delivered and acquired when there are proper institutional and constitutional frameworks between government and all stakeholders on how qualitative education is to be achieved to fit into the general societal goal or common good.}},
               {:contains_hatespeech => false, :title => "A vision that shaped the course of higher education", :date => DateTime.parse('December 3, 2012'), :link => "http://www.dailytrust.com.ng/index.php/other-sections/opinion/182478-a-vision-that-shaped-the-course-of-higher-education", :text => %{There is a sense in which it may be said that had the University of Nigeria not existed in the first place, the generation of post-independence leadership of the country would still have had to invent one. This is because, looking back now, the establishment of the university bordered on a historical mission, as encapsulated in the Report of the Economic Rehabilitation of Eastern Nigeria (1955) which made the case for the immediate establishment of a full-fledged university in the Region: “Such a higher institution of learning should not only be cultural, according to the classical concept of universities, but it should also be vocational in its objective and Nigerian in its content.” The dawn of political independence in Africa was all the more remarkable as it offered the new nations a context to dream lofty dreams. It needs be emphasized that, in the case of Rt. Hon. Nnamdi Azikiwe, the founder of the University of Nigeria, the original impulse for the establishment of the University ran far much deeper than the crush of independence. The reason the university will for a very long time to come remain the reference point in the development of higher education hinges on its history as a catalytic influence in the diversification of knowledge and the democratization of access to higher education. The introduction of vocational courses and the teaching of General Studies (GS) have bred an academic tradition that defines the mission of the public university. Through thick and thin, this tradition has largely held firm and constitutes the connecting thread in the tangled web of the institution’s history. Twenty seven ago, the University celebrated its silver jubilee anniversary. It was an auspicious occasion to reflect on the institution’s history and to contemplate its future. Onigu Otite, a pioneer graduate of the university and by then a professor of sociology at the University of Ibadan suggested at the time that the chequered origins of the school made its first 25 years appear to collapse centuries of the normal rise and fall of such institutions elsewhere. Inevitably, the ravages wrought by the ugly spectre of the Nigerian civil war have since become an integral part of the narrative of the University. Upon his return to the war-scarred institution in 1970, Dr D.R. Duncan, an Inter- University Council adviser from Cambridge University made a sobering observation of the patent devastation and destruction, on the one hand, and a burning determination and purpose to create something unique from the tragedy of the past, on the other. Despite a succession of national educational crises punctuated by internal upheavals, the University has grown in exponential terms ever since. The take-off student population of 220 in six foundation departments in 1960 and an academic staff strength of 13, which, by the 1962/63 session had shot up to 1,248 students in 27 departments and colleges, and a total of 160 lecturers, pales in comparison to the current student enrolment figure of about 35,000, academic staff and faculty population of 1,785, in addition to non-academic personnel of 5,420. In fifty years, the University has graduated over 125,000 students in various degrees and diplomas (compared to the first set of 150 graduates in 1963) and today boasts 106 departments, 15 faculties, 10 centres and 3 institutes spread across four campuses- Nsukka, Enugu, Ituku/Ozalla and Aba. With research at the heart of the founding of the university, post-graduate studies stand out as a beneficiary of the exponential growth of the institution.  Fresh from the ruins of war, the school conferred its first Master’s degree in 1971 and its first PhD four years later in 1975. In the 1978/79 session when the School of Post-graduate Studies came into existence, the post-graduate student enrolment figure stood at 288, but by 1984/85 session, the figure had risen to 1,309 students. By contrast, with all academic departments presently running fully functional post-graduate programmes, a total of 2,226 new students enrolled for various programmes under the school in the 2010/2011 session. Much has been made of the ennobling dreams of the founding fathers of the university, but in reality those dreams might have counted for little without the commensurate sweat and exertions, commitment and conviction of the men and women in the arena of teaching and research. As we mark the 52nd Founders Day this year, preparatory to celebrating the 50th anniversary of the pioneer set of university graduates from a Nigerian university in October 2013, I cannot but register once more my appreciation of the tortuous journey that started with the singular vision of Dr Azikiwe, former Premier of the Eastern Region, former President of Nigeria and foremost nationalist.}},
