            {:contains_hatespeech => false, :title => "Dance your way out of depression! ", :date => DateTime.parse('01 December 2012'), :link => "http://www.tribune.com.ng/news2013/index.php/en/component/k2/item/451-dance-your-way-out-of-depression". :author => "lessing Ekum", :text = %{Are you depressed and the thought of constantly having to down antidepressants is a turn off? BLESSING EKUM looks into new research findings that indicate that dancing may just be what you need. Depression is not just a state of sadness or listlessness. The US National Institute of Mental Health cite difficulty concentrating, remembering details, and making decisions; fatigue and decreased energy; feelings of guilt, worthlessness, and/or helplessness; feelings of hopelessness and/or pessimism; insomnia, early-morning wakefulness, or excessive sleeping; irritability, restlessness; loss of interest in activities or hobbies once pleasurable, including sex. Other symptoms include overeating or appetite loss; persistent aches or pains, headaches, cramps, or digestive problems that do not ease even with treatment; persistent sad, anxious, or “empty” feelings and thoughts of suicide, suicide attempts as symptoms. According to Psychology Information Online, depression ranks as one of the most prevalent psychological problems. In the United States, the Center for Disease Control and Prevention puts the figure at one in 10 American adults. Professor Oye Gureje of the department of Psychiatry, University of Ibadan, Oyo State, says about 20 per cent of women and 15 per cent of men in Nigeria will experience it in their lifetime. Dr. Adetokunbo Ajala of the Idi-Ape Medical Centre, Basorun, Ibadan, Oyo State, opines that quite a number of Nigerians would be prone to depression because of environmental factors, such as social and economic problems, that can trigger it. Sufferers of this condition are subjected to antidepressants and psychotherapy to help manage the condition. However, these drugs do not come without their load of side effects. As a result, medical researchers have delved into alternative treatments for depression and recent findings suggest that dancing can be linked to healthy mental health. Dancing is as old as man and has been used as a form of entertainment, communication and social interaction. But if research findings are anything to go by, then an additional benefit has been attributed to dance. In a study by Anna Duberg, a physical therapist and doctoral student at Rebro University Hospital, Sweden, an experiment was carried out on 112 Swedish girls aged 13 to 19. On multiple occasions, these girls had gone to see the school nurse complaining of anxiety and depression, fatigue, headaches, back, neck and shoulder pains. Fifty-nine of the girls were randomly selected and grouped into a group that regularly danced two days a week and 53 girls were the control group that did not change their living habits. The study results indicated that the girls in the dance group increased their self-esteem compared with the control group. The positive effect persisted at follow-ups four and eight months after the dance training ended. 91 per cent of the girls in the dance group felt that the dance study had been a positive experience. In another study by Mehibe Akandere of the School of Physical Education and Sport, Selcuk University, Konya, Turkey, it was discovered that depressed individuals who took classes in dance have been indicated to have an improved sense of psychological well-being and decreased anxiety and depression, thus enhancing the subjects’ self-perceptions of creativity, motivation, relaxation, health, intelligence, confidence, and energy. Besides, those who took the dance classes not only felt better about themselves than a similar group who took an academic course, they also felt better about themselves than students who participated in active sports. More researches carried out in recent years have also shown that dance and movement therapy help the treatment of physical trauma, cancer, nervous breakdowns, chronic pain, heart disease and post-surgical pain. It has been reported that dance has positive effects on self-concept, psychological well-being and lowers levels of anxiety and improves internal locus of control. Dr Ajala explains how dance could be a mood lifter. “Dancing is a rhythmical physical activity and such activities have been known to release certain neurotransmitters such as serotonin that improves mood and makes people happy. It also improves social interactions because people don’t usually dance alone and that is good for a depressed person,” he explains. So, is it alanta, etighi, azonto, street dancing or the more classical dance styles of tango, ballet and salsa, the choice is all yours. Whichever is your leaning, whenever you feel the blues, put on your dancing shoes!}},
